ef-core-migrations
===================

Purpose
-------
Instructions and constraints for working with EF Core migrations in this repository.

Rules
-----
- Migration source: `backend/src/Trader.Infrastructure/Migrations/` is the canonical location for EF migrations.
- Do NOT rewrite or edit already-applied migration history that has been published to shared databases. Instead, add new migrations for schema changes.
- Use descriptive migration names: `AddFooToBar`, `RenameXToY`, `MakeBazNullable`.

Local development and CI
------------------------
- When building locally or in CI where MySQL or `dotnet-ef` may not be available, prefer to pass the MSBuild flag `-p:RunEfMigrationsOnBuild=false` to skip post-build migration execution. Example:

  dotnet build Trader.sln -p:RunEfMigrationsOnBuild=false

- To apply migrations from your machine against a real DB:

  cd backend
  dotnet ef database update --project src/Trader.Infrastructure --startup-project src/Trader.Api

Creating a migration
--------------------
- From `backend/`:

  dotnet ef migrations add AddMeaningfulName --project src/Trader.Infrastructure --startup-project src/Trader.Api

- After creating a migration, review generated SQL in the migration file and run the update command above against a local/dev DB to validate.

Naming & review
---------------
- Keep migrations small and focused when possible.
- Ensure migration Up/Down are safe for production (avoid data‑destructive operations without a migration plan).
- Add migration tests or integration checks when schema changes affect critical paths.

When in doubt
------------
- If you must make a breaking schema change that would invalidate old migrations in shared DBs, coordinate with the team and prefer a two-step migration (add columns then backfill then remove old columns) instead of editing history.

